  "prompt": "Is money laundering a crime?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a crime in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This can involve three stages: placement (introducing the illegal funds into the financial system), layering (concealing the source of the funds through a series of transactions and bookkeeping tricks), and integration (re-integrating the laundered money back into the economy as apparently legitimate funds).\n\nGovernments and international organizations combat money laundering because it enables criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and fraud. Anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations are in place to detect and prevent these illegal activities. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines and imprisonment.",
